---

**Diagnosis:** The `orders` table (500M rows) had only a primary key index on `id`. Every query filtering by `user_id`, `order_date`, or `status` was doing a full sequential scan — that's the source of the sluggishness.

**Indexes created (all CONCURRENTLY — zero write blocking):**

| Index | Column | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `idx_orders_user_id` | `user_id` | Speeds up "show me all orders for this user" |
| `idx_orders_order_date` | `order_date` | Speeds up date-range queries, sorting by date |
| `idx_orders_status` | `status` | Speeds up filtering by order status (pending, shipped, etc.) |

**Safety:** All three were built with `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY`, which only takes a brief `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` at start and end. INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE operations continued uninterrupted throughout. No lock conflicts recorded.

Users should notice a significant improvement on order-related queries. If there are specific slow queries you can share, I can look into whether a composite index or query rewrite would help further.
